paragraphs:
[24]
The following provisions of the
Canadian Environmental Assessment Act
[see footnote 11] are relevant for the purposes of this judicial review.
"WHEREAS the Government of Canada seeks to achieve sustainable development by conserving and enhancing environmental quality and by encouraging and promoting economic development that conserves and enhances environmental quality;
"WHEREAS environmental assessment provides an effective means of integrating environmental factors into planning and decision-making processes in a manner that promotes sustainable development;
"WHEREAS the Government of Canada is committed to exercising leadership within Canada and internationally in anticipating and preventing the degradation of environmental quality and at the same time ensuring that economic development is compatible with the high value Canadians place on environmental quality;
"WHEREAS the Government of Canada is committed to facilitating public participation in the environmental assessment of projects to be carried out by or with the approval or assistance of the Government of Canada and providing access to the information on which those environmental assessments are based;
"2(1) In this Act,
. . . . .
'federal authority' means
(a) a Minister of the Crown in right of Canada,
. . . . .
'environmental assessment' means, in respect of a project, an assessment of the environmental effects of the project that is conducted in accordance with this Act and the regulations;
'project' means
(a) in relation to a physical work, any proposed construction, operation, modification, decommissioning, abandonment or other undertaking in relation to that physical work, or
. . . . .
'proponent', in respect of a project, means the person, body, federal authority or government that proposes the project;
. . . . .
'responsible authority', in relation to a project, means a federal authority that is required pursuant to subsection 11(1) to ensure that an environmental assessment of the project is conducted;
. . . . .
"4. The purposes of this Act are
(a) to ensure that the environmental effects of projects receive careful consideration before responsible authorities take actions in connection with them;
(b) to encourage responsible authorities to take actions that promote sustainable development and thereby achieve or maintain a healthy environment and a healthy economy;
(b.1) to ensure that responsible authorities carry out their responsibilities in a coordinated manner with a view to eliminate unnecessary duplication in the environmental assessment process;
(c) to ensure that projects that are to be carried out in Canada or on federal lands do not cause significant adverse environmental effects outside the jurisdictions in which the projects are carried out; and
(d) to ensure that there be an opportunity for public participation in the environmental assessment process.
"5(1) An environmental assessment of a project is required before a federal authority exercises one of the following powers or performs one of the following duties or functions in respect of a project, namely, where a federal authority
(a) is the proponent of the project and does any act or thing that commits the federal authority to carrying out the project in whole or in part;
(b) makes or authorizes payments or provides a guarantee for a loan or any other form of financial assistance to the proponent for the purpose of enabling the project to be carried out in whole or in part, except where the financial assistance is in the form of any reduction, avoidance, deferral, removal, refund, remission or other form of relief from the payment of any tax, duty or impost imposed under any Act of Parliament, unless that financial assistance is provided for the purpose of enabling an individual project specifically named in the Act, regulation or order that provides the relief to be carried out;
(c) has the administration of federal lands and sells, leases or otherwise disposes of those lands or any interests in those lands, or transfers the administration and control of those lands or interests to Her Majesty in right of a province, for the purpose of enabling the project to be carried out in whole or in part; gold"
"Whereas: the federal government aims for sustainable development through actions to conserve and improve the quality of the environment as well as to promote economic growth likely to contribute to the achievement of these ends;
"that environmental assessment constitutes an effective tool for taking environmental factors into account in planning and decision-making processes, so as to promote sustainable development;
"that the federal government commits to playing a leading role both nationally and internationally in preventing the high-value degradation that Canadians place on the environment;
"that the federal government undertakes to encourage public participation in the environmental assessment of projects to be undertaken by it or approved or assisted by it, as well as to provide access to the information on which this assessment is based,
"2(1) The following definitions apply in this Act.
. . . . .
'federal authority'
a) Federal Minister;
. . . . .
'environmental assessment' Assessment of the environmental effects of a project carried out in accordance with this Act and the regulations.
. . . . .
'project' Realization - including the operation, modification, decommissioning or closure - of a work or
. . . . .
'promoter' Federal authority or government, natural or legal person or any organization proposing a project.
. . . . .
'responsible authority' means the federal authority which, in accordance with subsection 11(1), is required to ensure that an environmental assessment of a project is carried out.
. . . . .
"4. The purpose of this law is:
(a) to allow responsible authorities to take action with respect to any project likely to have environmental effects based on informed judgment as to those effects;
b) to encourage these authorities to promote sustainable development conducive to environmental health and a healthy economy;
(b.1) to ensure that responsible authorities fulfill their obligations to avoid any duplication in the environmental assessment process;
(c) to ensure that any significant adverse environmental effects of projects to be carried out within the boundaries of Canada or federal lands do not extend beyond those boundaries;
(d) ensure that the public has the opportunity to participate in the environmental assessment process.
"5(1) The environmental assessment of a project is carried out before the exercise of one of the following powers:
(a) a federal authority is the promoter and implements it in whole or in part;
(b) a federal authority grants to a promoter with a view to helping him implement the project in whole or in part, financing, a loan guarantee or any other financial assistance, unless the financial assistance is granted in the form of relief - in particular reduction, avoidance, deferral, reimbursement, cancellation or remission - of a tax or an impost which is provided for under a federal law, unless this assistance is granted with a view to enabling the implementation of a particular project specified by name in the law, regulation or decree providing for the relief;
(c) a federal authority administers the federal territory and authorizes its transfer, in particular by sale or lease, or that of any land rights relating thereto or transfers administration and control to Her Majesty in right of a province, with a view to implementing the project in whole or in part;"
